Implementing a list of pairs using an `ArrayList` that contains *n* `Map.Entry` objects for a list of size *n* seems to me wasteful in both time and space.

So I created my own `PairList&lt;L, R&gt;` class that implements `List&lt;Map.Entry&lt;L, R&gt;&gt;` and stores the *n* entries in a backing list of size *2 * n*:
```
interface PairList&lt;L, R&gt; extends List&lt;Map.Entry&lt;L, R&gt;&gt; {
  static &lt;L, R&gt; PairList&lt;L, R&gt; of(); // creates empty mutable list
  boolean add(int index, L l, R r); // adds a pair
  boolean addAll(PairList&lt;L, R&gt; list); // adds all pairs in another list
  Map.Entry&lt;L, R&gt; set(int i, L l, R r); // updates pair i
  void forEach(BiConsumer&lt;L, R&gt; consumer); // iterates over pairs
  L left(int i); // returns the left part of pair i
  R right(int i); // returns the right part of pair i
  List&lt;L&gt; leftList(); // returns the left slice
  List&lt;R&gt; rightList(); // returns the right slice
  List&lt;T&gt; transform(BiFunction&lt;L, R, T&gt; f); // applies a mapping function
  ImmutablePairList&lt;L, R&gt; immutable(); // returns an immutable copy
}
```

The list contains the key of the first pair, the value of the first pair, the key of the second pair, and so forth. There are no `Map.Entry` objects.

If you wish to iterate over the list using a `for` loop or the `iterator()` method, the `Map.Entry` objects are created on the fly. But the `forEach(BiConsmer&lt;L, R&gt; consumer)` method performs [internal iteration][1], calling your consumer once for each pair. This is more efficient, because no `Map.Entry` objects are ever created.

In the following example, we create and populate a list, and iterate over it using internal and exterior iteration:
```
PairList&lt;String, Integer&gt; nameYears = PairList.of();
nameYears.add(&quot;Paul&quot;, 1942);
nameYears.add(&quot;John&quot;, 1940);
nameYears.add(&quot;Ringo&quot;, 1940);
nameYears.add(&quot;George&quot;, 1943);

// Exterior iteration
for (Map.Entry&lt;String, Integer&gt; pair: nameYears) {
  println(pair.getKey() + &quot; was born in &quot; + pair.getValue());
}

// Internal iteration
nameYears.forEach((name, year) -&gt; {
    println(name + &quot; was born in &quot; + year);
  });
```

There&#39;s also an immutable version, as follows:
```
interface ImmutablePairList&lt;L, R&gt; extends PairList&lt;L, R&gt; {
  static &lt;L, R&gt; ImmutablePairList&lt;L, R&gt; copyOf(Iterable&lt;Map.Entry&lt;L, R&gt; iterable);
  static &lt;L, R&gt; ImmutablePairList&lt;L, R&gt; of(); // empty immutable list
  static &lt;L, R&gt; ImmutablePairList&lt;L, R&gt; of(L l, R r, Object ... rest); // list with 1 or more pairs
}
```
Because it never needs to be resized,`ImmutablePairList` uses an even more efficient backing store than a mutable `PairList`: an `Object[]` of size *2 * n* holds the pairs.

You can find the implementation in my Morel project: [interface PairList][2]; feel free to copy it into your own code.


  [1]: https://wiki.c2.com/?InternalIterator
  [2]: https://github.com/hydromatic/morel/blob/main/src/main/java/net/hydromatic/morel/util/PairList.java#L46

If you&#39;re open to using a third-party library, [Eclipse Collections][1] has support for primitive pairs and primitive collections. This can reduce the amount of boxing required instead of using `Float` and `Short` wrapper objects, if that is a concern.

    @Test
    public void floatShortPairs() 
    {
        MutableList&lt;FloatShortPair&gt; pairs = Lists.mutable.of(
                PrimitiveTuples.pair(10.0f, (short) 10),
                PrimitiveTuples.pair(5.0f, (short) 5),
                PrimitiveTuples.pair(10.0f, (short) 5),
                PrimitiveTuples.pair(5.0f, (short) 10));
    
        FloatList floatList = pairs.collectFloat(pair -&gt; pair.getOne() * pair.getTwo());
        DoubleList doubleList = pairs.collectDouble(pair -&gt; pair.getOne() * pair.getTwo());
    
        FloatList expectedFloats = FloatLists.mutable.of(100.0f, 25.0f, 50.0f, 50.0f);
        Assertions.assertEquals(expectedFloats, floatList);
    
        DoubleList expectedDoubles = DoubleLists.mutable.of(100.0, 25.0, 50.0, 50.0);
        Assertions.assertEquals(expectedDoubles, doubleList);
    }

The `PrimitiveTuples` factory can create all combinations of primitive to primitive pairs. The `MutableList` interface has eager operations available directly on the collection to convert to other Object collections or primitive collections. These methods are prefixed with `collect`. `MutableList` extends the `java.util.List` interface.

