See [the documentation for `ArrayList#remove(int)`](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/ArrayList.html#remove%28int%29), as in the following syntax:

    list.remove(list.size() - 1)

Here is how it&#39;s implemented. `elementData` does a lookup on the backing array (so it can cut it loose from the array), which should be constant time (since the JVM knows the size of an object reference and the number of entries it can calculate the offset), and `numMoved` is `0` for this case:

    public E remove(int index) {
        rangeCheck(index); // throws an exception if out of bounds

        modCount++;        // each time a structural change happens
                           // used for ConcurrentModificationExceptions
        
        E oldValue = elementData(index);

        int numMoved = size - index - 1;
        if (numMoved &gt; 0)
            System.arraycopy(elementData, index+1, elementData, index,
                             numMoved);
        elementData[--size] = null; // Let gc do its work

        return oldValue;
    }

